A Go-based Temporal Workflow manages a long-running cluster with hundreds of nodes. It uses Update handlers to add/remove nodes and calls Continue-As-New when the history grows large. The team notices that occasionally, after a Continue-As-New, some in-flight Update requests appear to complete successfully on the client side but their effects are missing from the new Workflow run's state. Which of the following best explains the root cause and correct fix?

```go
func ClusterManagerWorkflow(ctx workflow.Context, input ClusterManagerInput) (ClusterManagerResult, error) {
    cm, _ := newClusterManager(ctx, input)
    workflow.SetUpdateHandler(ctx, "addNode", func(ctx workflow.Context, node string) error {
        cm.state.Nodes = append(cm.state.Nodes, node)
        return nil
    })
    for {
        workflow.Sleep(ctx, 10*time.Second)
        if cm.shouldContinueAsNew(ctx) {
            return ClusterManagerResult{}, workflow.NewContinueAsNewError(
                ctx, ClusterManagerWorkflow,
                ClusterManagerInput{State: &cm.state},
            )
        }
    }
}
```

A Go service uses an asynchronous Child Workflow pattern with `PARENT_CLOSE_POLICY_ABANDON` to fan out long-running jobs. The Parent Workflow calls `ExecuteChildWorkflow`, immediately returns `workflow.NewContinueAsNewError` to manage its own history growth, and expects the Child Workflows to keep running independently. In load testing, engineers observe that roughly 5–10% of Child Workflow Executions never appear in Temporal's visibility store. The Parent Workflow's history shows `StartChildWorkflowExecutionInitiated` for those missing children, but no `ChildWorkflowExecutionStarted` event. Which of the following is the correct explanation and remedy?

```go
func ParentWorkflow(ctx workflow.Context, input Input) error {
    for _, job := range input.Jobs {
        opts := workflow.ChildWorkflowOptions{
            ParentClosePolicy: enums.PARENT_CLOSE_POLICY_ABANDON,
        }
        ctx2 := workflow.WithChildOptions(ctx, opts)
        workflow.ExecuteChildWorkflow(ctx2, ChildWorkflow, job) // fire and forget
    }
    return workflow.NewContinueAsNewError(ctx, ParentWorkflow, nextInput)
}
```
